00:50:06.320 --> 00:50:10.371
But what I wondered most at
was, that, instead of

00:50:10.371 --> 00:50:13.409
tennis-balls,
they made use of books,

00:50:13.409 --> 00:50:17.039
seemingly stuffed with wind and
flocks;

00:50:17.039 --> 00:50:22.282
a thing marvellous and new:
but this I did not so much

00:50:22.282 --> 00:50:25.333
wonder at,
as to see, that whereas it is

00:50:25.333 --> 00:50:27.949
natural for winning gamesters to
rejoice,

00:50:27.949 --> 00:50:30.907
and losers to be sorry,
among the gamesters of that

00:50:30.907 --> 00:50:32.592
place,
all grumbled,

00:50:32.592 --> 00:50:35.980
all were upon the fret,
and all cursed one another.'

00:50:35.980 --> 00:50:39.045
'That is not at all strange,'
answered Sancho:

00:50:39.045 --> 00:50:41.019
'for devils,
play or not play,

00:50:41.019 --> 00:50:44.289
win or not win,
can never become contented.'

00:50:44.289 --> 00:50:47.170
[Sancho is knowledgeable about
what happens in hell,

00:50:47.170 --> 00:50:50.989
of course, he knows the oral
tradition about what is in hell,

00:50:50.989 --> 00:50:53.731
and how...]
'It is true,' quoth Altisidora:

00:50:53.731 --> 00:50:56.670
'but there is another thing I
wondered at,

00:50:56.670 --> 00:51:00.331
I mean, I wondered at it,
then [She has corrected

00:51:00.331 --> 00:51:02.434
herself,
because she's speaking in the

00:51:02.434 --> 00:51:03.722
present,
and she says no,

00:51:03.722 --> 00:51:08.257
no, and she's making it up,
again, remember that Dorotea

00:51:08.257 --> 00:51:12.065
makes a mistake,
also, and has to be corrected

00:51:12.065 --> 00:51:14.469
when she's making it up]
which was,

00:51:14.469 --> 00:51:17.289
that, at the first toss the
ball was demolished,

00:51:17.289 --> 00:51:19.719
and could not serve a second
time;

00:51:19.719 --> 00:51:23.510
and so they whipped them away,
and new and old,

00:51:23.510 --> 00:51:26.570
that it was marvelous to
behold: and to one of them,

00:51:26.570 --> 00:51:28.539
flaming new,
and neatly bound,

00:51:28.539 --> 00:51:32.771
they gave such a smart stroke,
that they made it its guts fly

00:51:32.771 --> 00:51:34.795
out,
and scattered its leaves all

00:51:34.795 --> 00:51:36.898
about,
and one devil said to another:

00:51:36.898 --> 00:51:38.809
"See what that book
is";

00:51:38.809 --> 00:51:42.277
and the other deviled answered:
"It is the Second Part

00:51:42.277 --> 00:51:45.119
of the History of Don Quixote de
la Mancha,

00:51:45.119 --> 00:51:48.960
not composed by Cid Hamet,
its first author,

00:51:48.960 --> 00:51:52.090
but by an Aragonese,
who calls himself a native of

00:51:52.090 --> 00:51:53.369
Tordesillas."
 

00:51:53.369 --> 00:51:55.634
[You have that on your cover of
Avellaneda's.]

00:51:55.634 --> 00:51:58.199
"Away with it,"
quoth the other devil,

00:51:58.199 --> 00:52:01.550
"and down with it to the
bottom of the infernal abyss,

00:52:01.550 --> 00:52:03.969
that my eyes may never see it
more."

00:52:03.969 --> 00:52:05.059
"Is it so bad?"
 

00:52:05.059 --> 00:52:06.360
answered the other.
 

00:52:06.360 --> 00:52:07.840
"So bad,"
replied the first,

00:52:07.840 --> 00:52:12.130
"that, had I myself
undertaken to make it worse,

00:52:12.130 --> 00:52:14.139
it had been past my skill."
 

00:52:14.139 --> 00:52:17.601
They went on with their play,
tossing other books and up and

00:52:17.601 --> 00:52:19.429
down...'"
And so forth.

00:52:19.429 --> 00:52:22.518
There is a lot of Dante in this
episode,

00:52:22.518 --> 00:52:26.460
but the story of devil's
playing a form of tennis,

00:52:26.460 --> 00:52:29.869
"pelota,"
with the souls or the heads of

00:52:29.869 --> 00:52:32.327
the dead,
is a traditional story,

00:52:32.327 --> 00:52:33.079
gruesome.
 

00:52:33.079 --> 00:52:39.190
But Cervantes has embroidered
upon it, by making them use

00:52:39.190 --> 00:52:44.320
books, instead of heads,
or souls, for balls.

00:52:44.320 --> 00:52:49.672
The attack on Avellaneda is
very funny, but the commentary

00:52:49.672 --> 00:52:54.650
on books goes beyond the
apocryphal Quixote.

00:52:54.650 --> 00:53:00.663
This episode reflects a change
in the appraisal of books by the

00:53:00.663 --> 00:53:05.610
beginning of the seventeenth
century in the west.

00:53:05.610 --> 00:53:09.000
Their value has diminished.
 

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:12.373
It seems to follow an
elementary economic law:

00:53:12.373 --> 00:53:16.570
with the advent of the printing
press the number of books

00:53:16.570 --> 00:53:20.414
increased dramatically,
and then, the value of each

00:53:20.414 --> 00:53:22.567
decreased--
I mean, this is basic

00:53:22.567 --> 00:53:25.780
economics--But it is more
complicated than that.

00:53:25.780 --> 00:53:30.967
Philosophy move toward
knowledge as a result of

00:53:30.967 --> 00:53:37.170
experience, not as something
acquired from authoritative

00:53:37.170 --> 00:53:41.570
sources whose works where in
books.

00:53:41.570 --> 00:53:45.545
In Spain neo-scholasticism,
about which you have read in

00:53:45.545 --> 00:53:48.161
Elliott,
which was a revival of the

00:53:48.161 --> 00:53:52.159
medieval philosophy of the
church fathers and which relied

00:53:52.159 --> 00:53:56.576
on syllogism and the opinion of
authoritative sources had become

00:53:56.576 --> 00:53:58.750
the ideology of the state.
 

00:53:58.750 --> 00:54:01.909
Neo-scholasticism,
doctrine, whatever you want to

00:54:01.909 --> 00:54:05.135
call it, and religious,
it was the ideology of the

00:54:05.135 --> 00:54:06.320
Spanish crown.
 

00:54:06.320 --> 00:54:10.721
Logic argumentation and
authorities supplied the

00:54:10.721 --> 00:54:13.250
foundations of knowledge.
 

00:54:13.250 --> 00:54:19.699
We have seen something of that,
and I mention it in the satire

00:54:19.699 --> 00:54:24.010
of doctors,
in the person of doctor Pedro

00:54:24.010 --> 00:54:27.820
Recio Tirteafuera who says to
Sancho,

00:54:27.820 --> 00:54:29.875
'you cannot eat this,
you cannot eat that,' the

00:54:29.875 --> 00:54:32.465
knowledge of medicine at the
time was based simply on books

00:54:32.465 --> 00:54:33.449
not on experience.
 

00:54:33.449 --> 00:54:37.800
So the situation in the rest of
Europe was not as extreme,

00:54:37.800 --> 00:54:41.043
by philosophical thought
nonetheless rejected bookish

00:54:41.043 --> 00:54:44.599
learning in favor of experience
and individual thought.

00:54:44.599 --> 00:54:48.619
The greatest exponent of this
was Descartes,

00:54:48.619 --> 00:54:51.795
whom I have mentioned several
times in the course of the

00:54:51.795 --> 00:54:53.443
semester,
and a precursor,

00:54:53.443 --> 00:54:56.007
if you wish,
although in a milder or lighter

00:54:56.007 --> 00:54:59.050
kind of philosophical
speculation was Montaigne.

00:54:59.050 --> 00:55:06.159
Anthony Grafton,
professor at Princeton,

00:55:06.159 --> 00:55:14.170
opens the introduction of his
magnificent book,

00:55:14.170 --> 00:55:17.608
New Worlds,
Ancient Texts: the Power

00:55:17.608 --> 00:55:22.500
of Tradition and the Shock of
Discovery with these words,

00:55:22.500 --> 00:55:27.619
quote: "Between 1550 and
1650 western thinkers ceased to

00:55:27.619 --> 00:55:32.655
believe that they could find all
important truths in ancient

00:55:32.655 --> 00:55:34.789
books." Unquote.
 

00:55:34.789 --> 00:55:38.530
Grafton goes on to quote Jesuit
JosÃ© de Acosta,

00:55:38.530 --> 00:55:48.500
 
 

00:55:48.500 --> 00:55:51.425
who published a very important
book, a very comprehensive book

00:55:51.425 --> 00:55:53.250
about the history of the New
World,

00:55:53.250 --> 00:56:03.219
called Historia natural y
moral,

00:56:03.219 --> 00:56:05.929
"moral"
means culture,

00:56:05.929 --> 00:56:09.079
"natural"
is physical,

00:56:09.079 --> 00:56:10.835
the nature and
"moral"

00:56:10.835 --> 00:56:14.190
means culture,
de las Indias.

00:56:14.190 --> 00:56:20.601
This book is from the 1590s,
1592, or something like that,

00:56:20.601 --> 00:56:22.739
I can't remember.
 

00:56:22.739 --> 00:56:26.893
But he says,
he quotes Acosta,

00:56:26.893 --> 00:56:31.619
who says the following,
quote:

00:56:31.619 --> 00:56:35.898
"Having read what poets
and philosophers write of the

00:56:35.898 --> 00:56:40.476
torrid zone I persuaded myself
that when I came to the equator

00:56:40.476 --> 00:56:43.704
[he's on a ship on his way to
the New World]

00:56:43.704 --> 00:56:47.833
I would not be able to endure
the heat but it turned out

00:56:47.833 --> 00:56:52.126
otherwise,
for when I passed the equator I

00:56:52.126 --> 00:56:57.304
felt so cold that I was forced
to go into the sun to warm

00:56:57.304 --> 00:56:58.230
myself.
 

00:56:58.230 --> 00:57:01.623
What could I do,
but laugh at Aristotle's

00:57:01.623 --> 00:57:03.320
meteorology?"
 

00:57:03.320 --> 00:57:05.409
Says Acosta.
 

00:57:05.409 --> 00:57:09.385
This is mocked,
by the way, in chapter XIX of

00:57:09.385 --> 00:57:12.297
Part II,
in the episode of the enchanted

00:57:12.297 --> 00:57:14.826
boat,
meaning that the actual

00:57:14.826 --> 00:57:19.929
experience of travel demolishes
traditional knowledge,

00:57:19.929 --> 00:57:23.313
the traditional knowledge being
whether Sancho's lice would die

00:57:23.313 --> 00:57:25.833
when they cross a certain line,
and so forth,

00:57:25.833 --> 00:57:28.730
remember all of that is mocked,
but this is what is behind it.

00:57:28.730 --> 00:57:31.869
Ironically, then,
the proliferation of books,

00:57:31.869 --> 00:57:36.369
being--at the time,
"when the authority of the

00:57:36.369 --> 00:57:41.949
book was most severely tested
and ultimately devalued."

00:57:41.949 --> 00:57:44.891
That is, the proliferation of
books takes place at the time

00:57:44.891 --> 00:57:47.934
"when the authority of the
book was most severely tested

00:57:47.934 --> 00:57:49.659
and ultimately devalued."
 

00:57:49.659 --> 00:57:56.422
The ability to read many books
did not bring one closer to

00:57:56.422 --> 00:58:02.498
wisdom but to an inordinate,
perhaps infinite enlargement of

00:58:02.498 --> 00:58:06.369
the library and perhaps to Don
Quixote's madness.

00:58:06.369 --> 00:58:11.744
I believe that this is what is
implicit in this marvelous

00:58:11.744 --> 00:58:16.159
passage of Altisidora's infernal
visitation.

00:58:16.159 --> 00:58:20.802
As customary,
Cervantes deals with very

00:58:20.802 --> 00:58:25.853
complicated issues,
in such an unaffected

00:58:25.853 --> 00:58:33.280
spontaneous and amusing way that
it seems almost like a miracle,

00:58:33.280 --> 00:58:39.510
but this is what is behind this
episode about books being

00:58:39.510 --> 00:58:43.849
whacked with burning flaming
rackets.

00:58:43.849 --> 00:58:49.996
We will be dealing chiefly with
the end of the Quixote in

00:58:49.996 --> 00:58:52.340
the last two lectures.
 

00:58:52.340 --> 00:58:58.000
 
 

